1
00:00:00,150 --> 00:00:02,520
How can you sit on a
beach, sipping a cocktail,

2
00:00:02,520 --> 00:00:05,620
and all the while, money is
rolling into your bank account?

3
00:00:05,620 --> 00:00:08,140
Well, it turns out this
is actually possible

4
00:00:08,140 --> 00:00:09,430
with something called...

5
00:00:09,430 --> 00:00:10,263
- Passive income.

6
00:00:10,263 --> 00:00:11,096
- Passive income.

7
00:00:11,096 --> 00:00:11,929
- Passive income.

8
00:00:11,929 --> 00:00:12,762
- Passive income.

9
00:00:12,762 --> 00:00:15,500
But when millions of people
are chasing the same dream,

10
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:17,010
things aren't gonna be easy.

11
00:00:17,010 --> 00:00:18,620
- Essentially, I'm broke.

12
00:00:18,620 --> 00:00:20,130
- I don't have any money left.

13
00:00:20,130 --> 00:00:21,470
- I filed bankruptcy.

14
00:00:21,470 --> 00:00:23,870
- That's why I've done some
digging, and compiled a list

15
00:00:23,870 --> 00:00:26,800
of 5.5 unique passive income ideas.

16
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:27,730
Let's talk about them.

17
00:00:27,730 --> 00:00:28,900
Hi guys, it's Mark.

18
00:00:28,900 --> 00:00:31,360
It's no surprise people love the idea

19
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:32,760
of not working for money,

20
00:00:32,760 --> 00:00:34,400
but if that was the reality,

21
00:00:34,400 --> 00:00:37,010
then we'd all be passive
income millionaires.

22
00:00:37,010 --> 00:00:39,230
Although passive income doesn't exist,

23
00:00:39,230 --> 00:00:41,140
leveraged income does.

24
00:00:41,140 --> 00:00:43,310
This is by far the most effective way

25
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:44,930
to earn money long term,

26
00:00:44,930 --> 00:00:47,250
and has enabled me to
become a millionaire.

27
00:00:47,250 --> 00:00:50,030
However, it also involves various risks,

28
00:00:50,030 --> 00:00:52,250
upfront investments of time and money,

29
00:00:52,250 --> 00:00:54,570
and plenty of good, old-fashioned work.

30
00:00:54,570 --> 00:00:56,840
Only highly motivated people will succeed

31
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:58,350
at creating leveraged income,

32
00:00:58,350 --> 00:01:00,670
as you first need to
take a large upfront risk

33
00:01:00,670 --> 00:01:02,460
in terms of time and/or money.

34
00:01:02,460 --> 00:01:03,770
This is so that in the future,

35
00:01:03,770 --> 00:01:07,010
you're able to earn more than
others could only dream of.

36
00:01:07,010 --> 00:01:10,250
Leveraged income is money
you get for creating value,

37
00:01:10,250 --> 00:01:12,930
and value comes from solving
a problem people have.

38
00:01:12,930 --> 00:01:14,260
The best problems to solve

39
00:01:14,260 --> 00:01:15,950
are the ones that aren't already flooded

40
00:01:15,950 --> 00:01:18,810
with lots of people
offering the same solution.

41
00:01:18,810 --> 00:01:21,190
This is known as finding blue oceans,

42
00:01:21,190 --> 00:01:23,960
as red ones are full of people
tearing each other apart,

43
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:25,990
competing for the same income.

44
00:01:25,990 --> 00:01:29,700
That's why I've made this
list of 5.5 unique ideas,

45
00:01:29,700 --> 00:01:32,410
so that you have a much
higher chance of success.

46
00:01:32,410 --> 00:01:34,620
Idea number one is Spotify playlists.

47
00:01:34,620 --> 00:01:37,760
This is 1 on the risk scale
and 2 on effort level.

48
00:01:37,760 --> 00:01:40,180
I haven't actually seen
anyone mention this idea

49
00:01:40,180 --> 00:01:42,300
in any other passive income video,

50
00:01:42,300 --> 00:01:44,010
so we're starting off strong,

51
00:01:44,010 --> 00:01:45,940
but what am I talking about?

52
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:46,773
Well, the other day,

53
00:01:46,773 --> 00:01:49,000
I was just flicking
through Instagram stories,

54
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:50,800
and I got an ad for a playlist.

55
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:54,230
I thought the music sounded
perfect for focused work,

56
00:01:54,230 --> 00:01:57,960
so I clicked on it and downloaded
the playlist on Spotify.

57
00:01:57,960 --> 00:01:59,530
I then thought nothing more of it,

58
00:01:59,530 --> 00:02:01,100
and went on with my day, as normal.

59
00:02:01,100 --> 00:02:02,410
Fast-forward to the next day,

60
00:02:02,410 --> 00:02:03,780
and I was getting bombarded

61
00:02:03,780 --> 00:02:05,940
with different Spotify playlist ads.

62
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:08,910
This is probably because I
interacted with the first ad,

63
00:02:08,910 --> 00:02:10,950
and now the floodgates were open.

64
00:02:10,950 --> 00:02:12,300
However, I then realized

65
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:15,310
the ads weren't being run
by Spotify themselves,

66
00:02:15,310 --> 00:02:17,250
it was all individual people.

67
00:02:17,250 --> 00:02:18,630
so that got me thinking.

68
00:02:18,630 --> 00:02:21,200
If people are prepared to
spend money running ads,

69
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:22,970
then they must be making a profit

70
00:02:22,970 --> 00:02:24,580
from owning these playlists.

71
00:02:24,580 --> 00:02:27,810
so I did a bit of digging, and
it turns out I was correct.

72
00:02:27,810 --> 00:02:30,120
This is a great way to
make leveraged income,

73
00:02:30,120 --> 00:02:32,900
especially if you don't have
a lot of money to begin with.

74
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:34,410
You just need to spend time

75
00:02:34,410 --> 00:02:37,940
putting together a solid
playlist in a specific genre,

76
00:02:37,940 --> 00:02:38,980
gain followers,

77
00:02:38,980 --> 00:02:41,350
and figure out a way
to make money from it.

78
00:02:41,350 --> 00:02:43,870
There seems to be two
main ways of doing this.

79
00:02:43,870 --> 00:02:46,530
I prefer the second, but
you may think differently.

80
00:02:46,530 --> 00:02:49,320
The first way is to charge
up-and-coming artists a fee

81
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:51,360
for getting featured on your playlist.

82
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:53,960
When new artists are trying
to break into the scene,

83
00:02:53,960 --> 00:02:57,660
they're interested in one
main thing, Spotify streams.

84
00:02:57,660 --> 00:03:00,640
This is why an engaged
playlist is so powerful,

85
00:03:00,640 --> 00:03:01,970
as once you've built it,

86
00:03:01,970 --> 00:03:03,410
you can supply that artist

87
00:03:03,410 --> 00:03:05,670
with a predictable amount
of monthly streams,

88
00:03:05,670 --> 00:03:06,840
and charge accordingly.

89
00:03:06,840 --> 00:03:09,070
You can even have a
different pricing structure

90
00:03:09,070 --> 00:03:11,970
depending on how close to
the top you place their song.

91
00:03:11,970 --> 00:03:13,390
This is certainly achievable,

92
00:03:13,390 --> 00:03:16,150
and I could see you making
thousands a month doing it.

93
00:03:16,150 --> 00:03:17,870
However, here are the issues.

94
00:03:17,870 --> 00:03:20,270
It's against Spotify's terms of service,

95
00:03:20,270 --> 00:03:21,710
and not very passive,

96
00:03:21,710 --> 00:03:23,580
as you have to be in
contact with the artists

97
00:03:23,580 --> 00:03:25,150
to sell song placements.

98
00:03:25,150 --> 00:03:27,310
The second way is to start a Patreon.

99
00:03:27,310 --> 00:03:29,890
An artist can sign up
to a monthly membership

100
00:03:29,890 --> 00:03:31,240
in return for the chance

101
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:33,330
to submit their music to your playlist.

102
00:03:33,330 --> 00:03:34,680
This is a lot more passive,

103
00:03:34,680 --> 00:03:37,230
as the money would be
coming in automatically

104
00:03:37,230 --> 00:03:38,620
on a monthly basis,

105
00:03:38,620 --> 00:03:40,670
and all you have to do is review music

106
00:03:40,670 --> 00:03:42,200
and update the playlist.

107
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:44,770
You could easily charge $5 a month,

108
00:03:44,770 --> 00:03:47,070
and if you get 1000 artists signed up,

109
00:03:47,070 --> 00:03:49,690
you could be making 5,000 per month.

110
00:03:49,690 --> 00:03:51,780
This way also feels less dishonest,

111
00:03:51,780 --> 00:03:54,070
as you can actually pick songs you enjoy

112
00:03:54,070 --> 00:03:57,430
rather than taking money to
put bad music on your playlist.

113
00:03:57,430 --> 00:04:00,020
The best thing of all is that
you can replicate the process

114
00:04:00,020 --> 00:04:01,540
as many times as you like,

115
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:07,120
Idea number two is actually
called Merch by Amazon.

116
00:04:07,120 --> 00:04:10,170
This is 1 on the risk scale
and 3 on effort level.

117
00:04:10,170 --> 00:04:12,690
One of my friends is a
reasonable digital artist

118
00:04:12,690 --> 00:04:15,440
and has been working on many
different designs for years.

119
00:04:15,440 --> 00:04:18,210
He thought a good way to turn
those designs into profit

120
00:04:18,210 --> 00:04:20,280
would be to sell printed T-shirts,

121
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:22,350
so he had thousands printed,

122
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:24,520
but unfortunately, none of them sold.

123
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:26,440
This was until he took a trip to Germany

124
00:04:26,440 --> 00:04:28,500
and displayed his T-shirts at an event.

125
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:31,320
One of the designs started
selling like crazy.

126
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:34,320
Unfortunately, he only had
a limited supply available,

127
00:04:34,320 --> 00:04:36,070
and was unable to meet the demand

128
00:04:36,070 --> 00:04:38,140
as he had already invested all his money

129
00:04:38,140 --> 00:04:39,870
into the stock that wasn't selling.

130
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:42,850
If only he'd known about Merch by Amazon,

131
00:04:42,850 --> 00:04:44,560
as he would've saved money up front

132
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:46,810
and tested the market a lot faster.

133
00:04:46,810 --> 00:04:50,610
Merch by Amazon is an on-demand
T-shirt printing service.

134
00:04:50,610 --> 00:04:53,340
It allows sellers to create
and list T-shirt designs

135
00:04:53,340 --> 00:04:54,770
on Amazon, for free.

136
00:04:54,770 --> 00:04:55,930
There are no upfront costs,

137
00:04:55,930 --> 00:04:57,200
and you get paid royalties

138
00:04:57,200 --> 00:04:59,200
when a customer buys your shirt.

139
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:01,730
All you need to do is upload your designs,

140
00:05:01,730 --> 00:05:03,770
choose the colors, and set a price,

141
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:06,110
then Amazon will take care of the rest.

142
00:05:06,110 --> 00:05:07,210
Just think about it.

143
00:05:07,210 --> 00:05:08,780
Going the traditional route means

144
00:05:08,780 --> 00:05:11,430
that if you have one design,
and you want to sell that

145
00:05:11,430 --> 00:05:14,880
in three colors, and four
sizes, to men and women,

146
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:17,720
that's 24 shirts, if
you only do one of each.

147
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:19,320
If 24 customers call you

148
00:05:19,320 --> 00:05:21,920
and all want a large,
male T-shirt in blue,

149
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:23,110
you can only sell one.

150
00:05:23,110 --> 00:05:25,430
Merch by Amazon takes
care of this for you,

151
00:05:25,430 --> 00:05:26,420
and also saves you

152
00:05:26,420 --> 00:05:28,620
from having to go to shows and exhibitions

153
00:05:28,620 --> 00:05:29,780
to find a market,

154
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:32,490
as Amazon already has
a huge one established.

155
00:05:32,490 --> 00:05:34,540
Like anything, the more effort you put

156
00:05:34,540 --> 00:05:36,410
in researching customer demand,

157
00:05:36,410 --> 00:05:37,540
the better you'll do.

158
00:05:37,540 --> 00:05:40,580
Just remember to avoid
any copyrighted content.

159
00:05:40,580 --> 00:05:43,880
This means you can't just start
printing T-shirts like this

160
00:05:43,880 --> 00:05:46,060
without getting permission from Disney.

161
00:05:46,060 --> 00:05:47,090
Storm Pooper!

162
00:05:47,090 --> 00:05:49,650
Idea number three is vending machines.

163
00:05:49,650 --> 00:05:52,810
This is 5 on the risk scale
and 4 on effort level,

164
00:05:52,810 --> 00:05:55,970
so this idea is clearly a lot
harder than the first two.

165
00:05:55,970 --> 00:05:57,060
However, Selecta

166
00:05:57,060 --> 00:05:59,220
is one of the biggest
vending machine companies

167
00:05:59,220 --> 00:06:00,053
in the world

168
00:06:00,053 --> 00:06:03,900
and they reported sales
of over 1 billion in 2021,

169
00:06:03,900 --> 00:06:05,213
which was up 3% on 2020.

170
00:06:06,310 --> 00:06:08,070
This shows that the market is growing,

171
00:06:08,070 --> 00:06:09,720
and the potential is huge.

172
00:06:09,720 --> 00:06:11,320
Before I had my own businesses,

173
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:13,280
I worked as a carpenter's apprentice,

174
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:14,650
and can still remember clearly

175
00:06:14,650 --> 00:06:17,150
the old vending machine in the workshop.

176
00:06:17,150 --> 00:06:20,820
It cost me 10 cents for a
cup of coffee, a bargain!

177
00:06:20,820 --> 00:06:22,290
It was such a good price

178
00:06:22,290 --> 00:06:24,830
that the machine was actually
losing my boss money,

179
00:06:24,830 --> 00:06:27,350
so he had a bit of a
predicament on his hands.

180
00:06:27,350 --> 00:06:30,350
The income wasn't high enough
to cover maintenance costs,

181
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:32,490
the machine took time to refill,

182
00:06:32,490 --> 00:06:34,130
and he couldn't raise the prices,

183
00:06:34,130 --> 00:06:35,700
as the machine was so old

184
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:37,510
and no one would've paid the extra.

185
00:06:37,510 --> 00:06:39,950
He was considering not
having a vending machine,

186
00:06:39,950 --> 00:06:41,250
but he knew it was important

187
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:43,150
for us to have hot drinks nearby.

188
00:06:43,150 --> 00:06:44,490
That's when a young guy,

189
00:06:44,490 --> 00:06:46,180
he couldn't have been much older than me,

190
00:06:46,180 --> 00:06:47,450
walked into the warehouse

191
00:06:47,450 --> 00:06:50,170
and offered my boss a deal
he just couldn't turn down.

192
00:06:50,170 --> 00:06:52,770
He offered to install
three new vending machines

193
00:06:52,770 --> 00:06:53,770
in the workshop

194
00:06:53,770 --> 00:06:54,900
and promised to take care

195
00:06:54,900 --> 00:06:57,650
of all maintenance issues and restocking,

196
00:06:57,650 --> 00:07:00,930
as well as giving him a
15% cut of the revenue,

197
00:07:00,930 --> 00:07:03,030
so not only could my
boss please his staff,

198
00:07:03,030 --> 00:07:04,950
he would also make a nice profit.

199
00:07:04,950 --> 00:07:06,410
The new machines were a hit

200
00:07:06,410 --> 00:07:08,850
and could justify charging higher prices

201
00:07:08,850 --> 00:07:10,340
because of the better quality.

202
00:07:10,340 --> 00:07:12,790
The guy who installed the
machines later revealed

203
00:07:12,790 --> 00:07:14,760
that we were his first customers,

204
00:07:14,760 --> 00:07:16,480
and now he has a huge business

205
00:07:16,480 --> 00:07:18,260
with machines throughout the state

206
00:07:18,260 --> 00:07:20,340
all paying him passive income.

207
00:07:20,340 --> 00:07:22,630
The key to a successful
vending machine income

208
00:07:22,630 --> 00:07:24,750
is to find great locations.

209
00:07:24,750 --> 00:07:26,990
Once you've identified
a few different spots

210
00:07:26,990 --> 00:07:28,790
and agreed a deal with the owner,

211
00:07:28,790 --> 00:07:30,380
you can then secure a machine

212
00:07:30,380 --> 00:07:32,390
that fits the customer's needs.

213
00:07:32,390 --> 00:07:34,180
There are lots of used vending machines

214
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:36,120
going for low prices online,

215
00:07:36,120 --> 00:07:38,450
which would be ideal if
you're just starting out.

216
00:07:38,450 --> 00:07:39,610
You could even get a loan,

217
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:42,400
and spread the payments,
using the profits.

218
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:44,570
When picking things to
put into the machines,

219
00:07:44,570 --> 00:07:46,710
it's a good idea to think about the demand

220
00:07:46,710 --> 00:07:48,510
in the specific location,

221
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:50,420
and slowly test out different ideas

222
00:07:50,420 --> 00:07:52,090
until you have the perfect mix.

223
00:07:52,090 --> 00:07:54,290
After this, it's just
a case of hiring staff

224
00:07:54,290 --> 00:07:55,930
and expanding your empire

225
00:07:55,930 --> 00:07:58,160
so you're able to be as
hands-off as possible.

226
00:07:58,160 --> 00:08:00,160
Idea number four is SaaS.

227
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:03,340
This is 5 on the risk scale,
and 5 on effort level.

228
00:08:03,340 --> 00:08:05,840
SaaS stands for software as a service.

229
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:08,090
The beauty of this idea
is that they often use

230
00:08:08,090 --> 00:08:10,430
a subscription-based pricing model,

231
00:08:10,430 --> 00:08:13,210
so instead of a customer
paying once for your software,

232
00:08:13,210 --> 00:08:15,690
they pay on an ongoing basis.

233
00:08:15,690 --> 00:08:17,900
This can be monthly or annually.

234
00:08:17,900 --> 00:08:18,733
This is great,

235
00:08:18,733 --> 00:08:21,070
as it gives you a
predictable leveraged income

236
00:08:21,070 --> 00:08:22,230
each and every month,

237
00:08:22,230 --> 00:08:25,910
and the opportunity for
explosive nonlinear growth.

238
00:08:25,910 --> 00:08:28,310
My best friend decided
to go down the SaaS route

239
00:08:28,310 --> 00:08:31,360
at the exact time I started
selling physical products.

240
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:32,920
He specialized in software

241
00:08:32,920 --> 00:08:36,680
that handled data for large
membership organizations.

242
00:08:36,680 --> 00:08:39,480
These clients would have
100,000-plus members

243
00:08:39,480 --> 00:08:42,230
so keeping track of all that
data was an issue for them.

244
00:08:42,230 --> 00:08:44,430
At first, he decided to sell his software

245
00:08:44,430 --> 00:08:45,990
as a one-time purchase.

246
00:08:45,990 --> 00:08:49,210
However, he always had to
search for new customers.

247
00:08:49,210 --> 00:08:52,070
When he made the switch to
a subscription-based model,

248
00:08:52,070 --> 00:08:55,070
he increased his average
customer lifetime value,

249
00:08:55,070 --> 00:08:57,380
and secured reliable leveraged income.

250
00:08:57,380 --> 00:08:59,230
He later went on to sell this business

251
00:08:59,230 --> 00:09:00,890
for multiple millions.

252
00:09:00,890 --> 00:09:03,040
In order to achieve success like this,

253
00:09:03,040 --> 00:09:04,590
you first need to pick the people

254
00:09:04,590 --> 00:09:06,640
your software is going to serve.

255
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:08,350
There are two main categories,

256
00:09:08,350 --> 00:09:10,230
businesses or consumers.

257
00:09:10,230 --> 00:09:13,780
Serving other businesses is
often seen as the least risky,

258
00:09:13,780 --> 00:09:15,860
as you can make more money per client

259
00:09:15,860 --> 00:09:17,810
than if you're selling to everyday people.

260
00:09:17,810 --> 00:09:19,200
Once you've got that nailed down,

261
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:21,940
you need to develop a
